The Economics of Violence
KOPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine, and elsewhere are constantly in the news, so many would likely say war.
But this proves to be a great mistake.
The correct answer matters if we want to find cost-effective solutions to this and other global problems.
It goes without saying that everyone would like to end every war and act of violence, just as we would like to end poverty, hunger, and climate change, and ensure access to education for all people.
However, given limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We need to set priorities, and one way to do this is through an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to evaluate which goals they believe would be most wise.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the investment of funds that could otherwise, for example, be used to combat hunger?
And if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at Oxford University, violence in society—murders and especially violence against women and children—poses a much greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die due to interpersonal violence, and for every two combatants who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and too many countries record murder rates of over 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization describes as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs society 9.1 million US dollars.
Measured by national wealth globally, this form of violent crime alone costs 1.7% of the global gross social product (GSP).
Naturally, this is not a direct financial loss for the world economy, but a way to express the consequences.
If murders could be eliminated, societies around the world would be in a state that could be measured in terms of 1.7% of GSP.
Compare this with the much lower costs of civil wars, which amount to about 0.2% of the worldwide GIP.
However, this is still much less than the biggest source of violence at all: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the scientific journal Science, 28% of all women in Sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence from their partners or family members last year.
This includes women who were beaten, forced into marriage at a young age, subjected to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honor," and female genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal costs of violence by intimate partners amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars or 5.2% of global GDP.
The second-largest source of violence is child abuse, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of what constitutes child abuse varies from culture to culture, but roughly 15% of children experience what the UN considers severe physical punishment every month.
Herein include slaps to the face, head, or ears, and a quarter of these children are beaten repeatedly and as severely as possible with an object.
This suffering affects around 290 million children every month.
The social costs amount to 3.6 trillion US dollars or 4.2% of global GDP.
A tiny fraction of international aid currently flows towards reducing violence in society and improving criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and individuals cry out for action.
Unfortunately, there are still few secure insights into where the limited funds should be used most effectively.
All that can be said is that the money spent on reducing violence could be used more targetedly.
Large sums of aid are intended for "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the component "crime prevention."
Other programs can contribute indirectly, but clearly much could be improved.
Some solutions, it is clear, work very well.
More effective social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the US state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve the quality of life for children and their physical and mental health, and lower the costs of care and legal proceedings.
A dollar spent on this program generates a benefit worth 14 US dollars: thus, it is an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes need to change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program called SASA! is being implemented in Uganda.
(Swahili for "Now!") to spread the idea that violence in partnerships is unacceptable and contributed to halving the number of cases.
This is a fantastic result, even though no analysis of cost efficiency was conducted.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures have been taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach—limiting alcohol sales, reclaiming public spaces, and improving police and justice systems—the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004.
This is still a high number, but far below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many physical attacks, and the insights from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of crucial importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on better enforcement of existing regulations showed that physical attacks could be reduced in a very cost-effective manner, with benefits outweighing costs by a ratio of 17 to 1.
While we do not know enough yet, two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children incurs societal costs amounting to 8 trillion US dollars per year and thus represents a huge – and much underestimated – global problem.
Second, there are solutions that can address some of these problems in a very cost-efficient way.
For this reason, reducing domestic violence should be among the priorities for the next set of global development goals.
